    "id": "anemia-falciforme",
    "nombreEs": "Anemia Falciforme (Enfermedad de Celulas Falciformes)",
    "nombreEn": "Sickle Cell Disease",
    "descripcionEs": "La anemia falciforme es una hemoglobinopatia hereditaria autosomica recesiva causada por una mutacion puntual en el gen HBB (beta-globina) localizado en el cromosoma 11p15.4. La mutacion p.Glu6Val (sustitucion de acido glutamico por valina en la posicion 6 de la cadena de beta-globina) produce la hemoglobina S (HbS), que al desoxigenarse polimeriza y deforma los eritrocitos adoptando forma de hoz o media luna. Estos eritrocitos falciformes son rigidos, adherentes y fragiles, causando oclusiones vasculares, hemolisis cronica y dano organico progresivo. Es la enfermedad genetica monogenica mas prevalente a nivel mundial, afectando aproximadamente a 300,000 recien nacidos anualmente, con mayor frecuencia en poblaciones de Africa subsahariana, Mediterraneo, Medio Oriente e India. El estado de portador heterocigoto (rasgo falciforme) confiere proteccion parcial contra la malaria por Plasmodium falciparum, lo que explica la alta prevalencia en regiones endemicas de malaria.",
    "descripcionEn": "Sickle cell disease is an autosomal recessive hereditary hemoglobinopathy caused by a point mutation in the HBB gene (beta-globin) located on chromosome 11p15.4. The p.Glu6Val mutation (substitution of glutamic acid for valine at position 6 of the beta-globin chain) produces hemoglobin S (HbS), which upon deoxygenation polymerizes and deforms red blood cells into a sickle or crescent shape. These sickled erythrocytes are rigid, adherent, and fragile, causing vascular occlusions, chronic hemolysis, and progressive organ damage. It is the most prevalent monogenic genetic disease worldwide, affecting approximately 300,000 newborns annually, with greatest frequency in populations from sub-Saharan Africa, the Mediterranean, Middle East, and India. The heterozygous carrier state (sickle cell trait) confers partial protection against Plasmodium falciparum malaria, which explains the high prevalence in malaria-endemic regions.",
